The CS50 Foundation (The "Why")

At the hardware level, a CPU executes instructions sequentially. Control flow forces the CPU to "jump" to different memory addresses based on conditions.

1. Conditional Branching at the Bytecode Level
When Python compiles your code into bytecode (before running it in the CPython virtual machine),
an if statement translates to conditional jump instructions like POP_JUMP_IF_FALSE.

if user.is_authenticated:
    show_dashboard()

Under the hood, Python evaluates the truthiness of the condition.
If it is false, the interpreter immediately changes its instruction pointer to skip the block. 
This evaluation is highly optimized and executes in constant time, $O(1)$.2. 
The Iterator Protocol (How Loops Actually Work)In languages like C or Java, a for loop traditionally increments an index counter (i++) to access an array layout in memory.
Python does not do this.In Python, a for loop is syntactic sugar for an architectural mechanism called the Iterator Protocol.
When you write for item in modern_list:, 
Python secretly does the following behind the scenes:It calls iter(modern_list), which returns an iterator object containing a __next__() method.
It repeatedly calls __next__() on that iterator to pull the next element.When there are no elements left, the iterator raises a StopIteration exception. 
Python catches this exception silently and exits the loop.
This architecture means Python loops can iterate over anything that implements the iterator protocol (files, database streams, network sockets), not just arrays.

